<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-02-17T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-02-17T18:00:00-05:00" n="1219" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1219">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M) Turkey/340:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Matthews</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi><note n="54" xml:id="d1219fn54">Repeated to the Ambassador in
                                Turkey in telegram No. 157, February 22, 10 p.m.</note>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-02-18T00:00:00+01:00">February
                                    18, 1943—midnight.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received February 19—12:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1275. I took up with the Foreign Office this morning the subject matter
                            of the Department’s telegram No. 1052, February 17, 1 p.m. and was given
                            oral assurances by Sir Orme Sargent<note n="55" xml:id="d1219fn55">British Deputy Under Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs.</note>
                            that appropriate instructions would be sent to the British Ambassador at
                                Ankara.<note n="56" xml:id="d1219fn56">Sir Hughe M.
                                Knatchbull-Hugessen.</note> He welcomed the suggestion and remarked
                            that one of the principal problems at present with regard to chrome
                            above ground is the need of vigilance to avoid “pilfering” and to hasten
                            transport from the mines to ports.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Matthews</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>